	<div id="share">
		<ul><li><p id="print"><a href="javascript:window.print();">Print this Page</a></li></ul>
	
	</div>
	
	
	
	
		
			<p><font size="3"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial; mso-bidi-font-family: " roman??="" new="" times="">The </span><place /><placetype /><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial; mso-bidi-font-family: " roman??="" new="" times="">University</span></placetype /><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial; mso-bidi-font-family: " roman??="" new="" times=""> of </span><placename /><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial; mso-bidi-font-family: " roman??="" new="" times="">Central Florida</span></placename /></place /><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial; mso-bidi-font-family: " roman??="" new="" times=""> and local businesses have quickly come to the aid of 47 students who were forced out of their Pegasus Pointe homes by a Wednesday morning fire.</span></font></p><p /><p><font size="3"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial; mso-bidi-font-family: " roman??="" new="" times="">College Park Communities, the company that manages the UCF-affiliated Pegasus Pointe and Pegasus Landing apartments, helped students find new homes in those complexes by Wednesday afternoon. The American Red Cross, CVS and Bed, </span><city /><place /><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial; mso-bidi-font-family: " roman??="" new="" times="">Bath</span></place /></city /><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial; mso-bidi-font-family: " roman??="" new="" times=""> and Beyond donated money, toiletries, sheets and blankets.</span></font></p><p /><p><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial; mso-bidi-font-family: 'Times New Roman'"><font size="3">Volunteer UCF, an organization of student volunteers, collected several bags of clothing Thursday from faculty and students and planned to continue collecting toiletries, towels and household items for about two weeks. Donated items can be dropped off at the Office of Student Involvement in Room 208 of the Student Union.</font></span></p><p /><p><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial; mso-bidi-font-family: " roman??="" new="" times=""><font size="3">Tracy Furr, a graduate student assistant with Volunteer UCF, said shed like to connect enough donations in the next couple of weeks to provide some help to all of the fire victims.</font></span></p><p /><p><font size="3"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial; mso-bidi-font-family: " roman??="" new="" times="">UCF Police and </span><place /><placename /><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial; mso-bidi-font-family: " roman??="" new="" times="">Orange</span></placename /><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial; mso-bidi-font-family: " roman??="" new="" times=""> </span><placetype /><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial; mso-bidi-font-family: " roman??="" new="" times="">County</span></placetype /></place /><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial; mso-bidi-font-family: " roman??="" new="" times=""> firefighters were called to Pegasus Pointe, about a mile south of UCF on Alafaya Trail, at </span><time hour="6" minute="25" /><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial; mso-bidi-font-family: " roman??="" new="" times="">6:25 a.m.</span></time /><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial; mso-bidi-font-family: " roman??="" new="" times=""> Wednesday. The building's 47 residents were evacuated immediately and the fire was under control by </span><time hour="8" minute="30" /><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial; mso-bidi-font-family: " roman??="" new="" times="">8:30 a.m.</span></time /><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial; mso-bidi-font-family: " roman??="" new="" times="">, according to officials on the scene. </span></font></p><p /><p><font size="3"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial">None of the residents was injured. One student was treated for minor smoke inhalation, a fire official said.</span></font></p>
		
	
		
			<p><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial; mso-bidi-font-family: " roman??="" new="" times=""><font size="3">Donations began arriving shortly after the fire. UCF resident assistants donated $500 from a charity fund they started at the beginning of the semester, and Barnes &amp; Noble, which runs the UCF Bookstore, offered to pay to replace textbooks that students lost during the fire. The UCFCard Office agreed to give the students new UCF identification cards for free.</font></span></p><p /><p><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial; mso-bidi-font-family: " roman??="" new="" times=""><font size="3">Craig Ullom, associate vice president for campus life at UCF, said the university will survey fire victims Monday to find out what they still need and how the university can assist them. UCF victim advocates met Wednesday evening with parents and students to help them cope with the situation.</font></span></p><p><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial; mso-bidi-font-family: " roman??="" new="" times=""><font size="3"></font></span></p><p><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial; mso-bidi-font-family: 'Times New Roman'"><font size="3">UCF Provost Terry Hickey sent an e-mail to professors Thursday asking them to be considerate of the needs of students whose homes were damaged in the fire. </font></span></p><p><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial; mso-bidi-font-family: " roman??="" new="" times=""><font size="3"><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial; mso-bidi-font-family: "Times New Roman"">Im most pleased that everybody is safe, Ullom said, adding that hes pleased with the outpouring of support so far from the UCF community and businesses.<p /></span></font></span><p><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial; mso-bidi-font-family: " roman??="" new="" times=""><font size="3">Authorities said the fire, which started on the third floor and spread to the attic, was caused by a cigarette that was left unattended in a patio chair.</font></span></p><p /><p><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial; mso-bidi-font-family: " roman??="" new="" times=""><font size="3">The building will likely have to be completely rebuilt and damaged siding on adjacent buildings will have to be replaced.</font></span></p><p /><p><span style="FONT-FAMILY: Arial; mso-bidi-font-family: " roman??="" new="" times=""><font size="3">Businesses and residents interested in making donations to help the students can contact Christi Hartzler, director of Housing &amp; Residence Life, at 407-823-4663. Call 407-823-6471 for more information about donations of toiletries, clothing and household items through Volunteer UCF.</font></span></p></p>
		
	
	<p id="back"><a href="index?page=news">&lt; Back to the Newsroom</a></p>

